  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and organizations that work to combat money laundering, including:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards\n- Develops recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides a framework for international cooperation against money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes guidelines for banks to prevent financial crimes\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Helps countries develop anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (U.S. law with international implications)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nMost countries have their own national laws that align with these international standards, requiring banks and financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report large or suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence on financial activities\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income and to track potential financial crimes.",
